âœ… 1. Which product lines generate the highest total sales?

Columns needed: PRODUCTLINE, SALES

Best visualization: Bar Chart / Column Chart

Insight: Helps identify top-performing product categories.

âœ… 2. How do monthly sales trend across different years?

Columns needed: ORDERDATE (or MONTH_ID + YEAR_ID), SALES

Best visualization: Line Chart

Insight: Reveals seasonality, growth patterns, and year-to-year changes.

âœ… 3. Which countries or territories contribute the most to sales?

Columns: COUNTRY or TERRITORY + SALES

Best visualization: Bar Chart / Map Chart (if available)

Insight: Shows geographic performance and market strength.

âœ… 4. How is order quantity related to deal size?

Columns: QUANTITYORDERED, DEALSIZE

Best visualization:

Box Plot (distribution by deal size)

Column Chart (quantity vs deal size category)

Insight: Shows how different deal size categories affect order volumes.

âœ… 5. Who are the top 10 customers by total purchase value?

Columns: CUSTOMERNAME, SALES

Best visualization: Horizontal Bar Chart

Insight: Spotlight major customers contributing most to revenue.

ğŸ“Š PIVOT CHARTS IN EXCEL â€” THE BASICS

A Pivot Chart is a visual representation of a Pivot Table.
It allows you to summarize, analyze, explore, and visualize your data quickly.

ğŸ§­ 1. HOW TO CREATE A PIVOT CHART
Option A â€” From a Pivot Table

Click anywhere inside your Pivot Table.

Go to PivotTable Analyze (or Options) tab.

Click PivotChart.

Choose the chart type (Column, Line, Pie, etc.).

Click OK.

Option B â€” Create Pivot Table + Pivot Chart Together

Select your data range.

Go to Insert â†’ PivotChart.

Choose where to place it (New Worksheet or Existing).

Click OK.
Excel creates PivotTable + PivotChart side-by-side.

ğŸ§© 2. HOW A PIVOT CHART WORKS

A Pivot Chart has Fields just like a Pivot Table. They are:

Filters

Axis (Categories)

Legend (Series)

Values

You drag fields into these sections to shape your chart.

ğŸ“˜ 3. EXAMPLES USING YOUR DATASET

Below are Pivot Chart setups you can build immediately from your columns.

ğŸ“Š Example 1: Sales by Product Line

Fields Setup:

Rows/Axis â†’ PRODUCTLINE

Values â†’ SUM of SALES

Chart Type:

Column Chart

Insight: Which product lines generate the most revenue?

ğŸ“ˆ Example 2: Monthly Sales Trend

Fields Setup:

Axis â†’ MONTH_ID

Legend (Optional) â†’ YEAR_ID

Values â†’ SUM of SALES

Chart Type:

Line Chart

Insight: How sales move month to month and year to year.

ğŸŒ Example 3: Sales by Country or Territory

Fields Setup:

Axis â†’ COUNTRY or TERRITORY

Values â†’ SUM of SALES

Chart Type:

Bar Chart

Insight: Your geographic sales performance.

ğŸ‘¥ Example 4: Deal Size vs Order Quantity

Fields Setup:

Axis â†’ DEALSIZE

Values â†’ AVERAGE of QUANTITYORDERED (or SUM)

Chart Type:

Column Chart or Box Chart (if using Power BI)

Insight: Which deal sizes drive bigger orders?

ğŸ›’ Example 5: Top Customers

Fields Setup:

Axis â†’ CUSTOMERNAME

Values â†’ SUM of SALES

Sort â†’ Largest to smallest

Filter â†’ Top 10

Chart Type:

Horizontal Bar Chart

Insight: Your top revenue-generating customers.

ğŸ¨ 4. CUSTOMIZING A PIVOT CHART

You can modify Pivot Charts the same way as normal charts:

Add chart title

Add data labels

Change colors

Change chart type

Filter directly through dropdowns

Expand/collapse categories

Use slicers to interact with the chart

ğŸ—‚ï¸ 5. CONNECTING MULTIPLE PIVOT CHARTS

If you have several Pivot Charts on your dashboard:

Go to Insert â†’ Slicer

Select fields (e.g., YEAR_ID, PRODUCTLINE, STATUS)

Connect slicer to multiple PivotTables

All charts update at once ğŸ‰

